.UPDATE...
Issued at 848 AM PDT Sun Mar 8 2026

Temperatures around the Bay Area are running up to 10 degrees
below this time yesterday while the Central Coast is +/- 5
degrees. Going by the how does it feel metric, it is a little
cooler this morning. While the winds just off the surface have
been out of the Northeast, offshore, this morning, as borne out by
the 12Z balloon, they are a lot weaker than this time yesterday.
As such, we`re not seeing the adiabatic compression and
subsequent warming in areas likes Sonoma. Hence the drop of about
7 to 15 degrees this morning. That said, even the weak offshore
flow has done its job in providing us generally clear skies for
the sunrise. Overall the forecast looks solid with warming again
today and a marine layer returning tonight. No updates needed.

&&

.SHORT TERM...
Issued at 308 AM PDT Sun Mar 8 2026
(Today and tonight)

The channel of N/NE low level boundary layer offshore flow across
the North Bay and Bay Area is gradually easing overnight and will
eventually shift to weak onshore flow by late this afternoon into
the evening hours. While H50 heights will lower slightly through the
day, thickness values will moderate increase over our area
throughout the day. The net result will be another warm and sunny
day area wide, likely a couple of degrees warmer than Saturday, with
noticeably less breezy conditions. Near-shore coastal locations will
once again be in the upper 60s to low 70s with the rest of the
interior in the mid/upper 70s and pockets of low 80s at higher
elevations. Overnight lows will drop a couple of degrees into Monday
from this mornings values with the return of onshore flow, however
weak it may be, and falling H50 heights.

&&

.LONG TERM...
Issued at 308 AM PDT Sun Mar 8 2026
(Monday through Saturday)

The stalled upper low south of SOCAL off the Baja coast will slowly
begin to move onshore Monday. While the upper low eventually
combines with the polar jet downstream Tuesday, we`ll see a
horizontal shortwave ridge axis responsible for the aforementioned
weak onshore flow shift south and east, bringing increasing clouds
and slightly cooler temps onshore. Tuesday will be the coolest
day of the week, as broader larger scale ridging appears to build
offshore through the remainder of the extended forecast with
temperatures similar to today returning for the end of the week
into next weekend. No rain in sight through the forecast period.

